'''Baluwatar''' ({{lang-ne|बालुवाटार}}) (also [[Kathmandu Metropolitan City]] Ward 04<ref>{{cite web |title=Ward 09 |url=http://www.kathmandu.gov.np/sites/kathmandu.gov.np/files/ward%204.pdf |publisher=Kathmandu Metropolitan City |accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>) is a residential area of [[Kathmandu]], the capital city of [[Nepal]] on the banks of [[Bagmati River]]. It is just 15 minutes away from what is known as the downtown of Kathmandu, [[New Road of Kathmandu|New Road]] and Ason and shares borders with [[Lazimpat]] and [[Gairidhara]].
Baluwatar hosts the [[Prime Minister of Nepal]]'s official residence, government offices, [[Nepal Rastra Bank|Nepal Rastra Bank's headquarters]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Contact Us|url=https://nrb.org.np/aboutus/contactus.php|publisher=Nepal Rastra Bank|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>, the Nepalese country headquarter of the [[International Organization for Migration]]<ref>{{cite web |title=IOM Country Office |url=http://nepal.iom.int/jupgrade/index.php/en/contact |publisher=IOM |accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> the Russian Embassy and the office of Volunteer Service and Support Nepal (VSSN) are located here.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}

A Nepal Army's Para Special Forces Battalion (Bhairab Dal) and Air Wing, TU Teaching Hospital, [[Nepal Police|Nepal Police Headquarters]] and the home of the former King Gyanendra and the current Presidential Palace are in the vicinity. There are some schools such as Meridian International School, Shiva Puri secondary school and many others. It is the most infrastructural developed city in Nepal due to place of  prime minister's residence.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}

In 2012, [[Occupy Baluwatar]] of the [[occupy movement]] was apeaceful protest movement calling on the Nepali state to better address the widespread problem of impunity and gender-based violence.<ref>{{cite web |title=A look back at Occupy Baluwatar |url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2014-01-17/a-look-back-at-occupy-baluwatar-258319.html |publisher=The Kathmandu Post |accessdate=1 August 2018 |date=17 January 2014}}</ref>

