'''Mary Ann Rocque''', born '''Mary Ann Scalé''' was a woman cartographer in 18th-century London.

The eldest sister of [[Bernard Scalé]], Mary Ann married Edward Bew at some point before 1743.<ref>J. H. Andrews, [http://www.irishgeography.ie/index.php/irishgeography/article/viewFile/1032/894 The French School of Dublin Land Surveyors], pp.284, 291n18</ref> In 1751 she became the second wife of cartographer [[John Rocque]]. After his death in 1762 she carried on the family business,<ref>Laura Bliss, [https://www.citylab.com/design/2016/03/women-in-cartography-early-north-america/471609/ The Hidden Histories of Maps Made By Women: Early North America], ''CityLab'', March 21, 1016</ref> going into partnership with Andrew Dury.<ref name="MacnairRowe2015">{{cite book|author1=Andrew Macnair|author2=Anne Rowe|author3=Tom Williamson|title=Dury and Andrews Map of Hertfordshire: Society and landscape in the eighteenth century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IBYDDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 |year=2015|publisher=Windgather Press |isbn=978-1-909686-74-8 |page=50}}</ref> In 1765 she published ''A Set of Plans and Forts of America''.<ref name="Hoonaard2013">{{cite book|author=Will C. van den Hoonaard|title=Map Worlds: A History of Women in Cartography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VY_ZAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT61 |year=2013 |publisher=Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press|isbn=978-1-55458-934-0|page=61}}</ref>

